      <h2>Can You Really Get a Quality Work Boot Under $100?</h2>
      <p>Yes — but you need to be honest about what you're getting. Budget boots use synthetic materials or split-grain leather instead of full-grain. The soles are often glued rather than stitched. Insoles are basic foam rather than advanced orthotic support.</p>
      <p>Here's the trade-off: a $60 boot will typically last 6–9 months of daily construction work. A $180 boot might last 18–24 months. So in pure cost-per-month terms, the budget boot can actually be cheaper. The difference is longevity and long-term foot comfort.</p>
      <p>If you're just starting out in the trades, working part-time, or need a backup pair, budget boots are a smart choice. If you're on a crew 50+ hours a week, investing in a pair like the Heavy Duty Steel Toe Leather Boots (just under $100) gives you the best balance of affordability and durability.</p>

      <h2>Tips to Make Budget Boots Last Longer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Replace the insoles immediately.</strong> Budget boots come with cheap foam insoles. A $15 pair of gel or memory foam insoles dramatically improves comfort and extends the boot's usable life.</li>
        <li><strong>Use waterproofing spray.</strong> Most synthetic budget boots are not naturally waterproof. A $10 can of silicone waterproofing spray applied every few weeks adds protection against wet job sites.</li>
        <li><strong>Let them dry out.</strong> Never store wet boots in a locker or car trunk. Stuff them with newspaper overnight to absorb moisture and prevent the glue from degrading.</li>
        <li><strong>Rotate if possible.</strong> Even one extra pair lets boots dry for 24 hours between wears, which can double the lifespan.</li>
      </ul>

